A:

From the book "Calculus" by James K. Lawler, p. 40:

The length of a straight line segment is the distance between the
  intersection of the segment and the point where the line joins the
  segment.

So the answer is the length of the segment.

A:

A line segment is given by the equation:
$$(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2=|x-a||y-b|$$
with $a$ the center and $b$ the two endpoints of the segment.
This equation can be solved for $x$ and $y$.  The solution is:
$$x=a+2\sqrt{a^2-b^2}$$
$$y=b+2\sqrt{a^2-b^2}$$
The length of the line is then:
$$|x-a||y-b|=\sqrt{a^2-b^2}-2\sqrt{a^2-b^2}$$
$$=2\sqrt{a^2-b^2}+2\sqrt{a^2-b^2}$$
$$=\sqrt{a^2-b^2}$$
